<section class="faq" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
  <div class="section-head">
    <span class="section-eyebrow" id="faq-heading">&#9670; COMMON QUESTIONS</span>
    <span class="section-rule"></span>
  </div>
  <div class="faq-list">
    <div class="faq-item">
      <h2 class="faq-q">Can I exclude sale items from discount codes natively on Shopify?</h2>
      <p class="faq-a">No. There is no exclude sale items setting anywhere in Shopify's discount screens. The combination settings decide how discounts combine with other discounts, but a sale you run by lowering prices and setting a compare-at price is not a discount to the engine, it is just a price, so codes apply to marked-down items exactly as they do to full-price ones. The nearest native route is eligibility: build an automated collection keyed off compare-at prices so sale items gather in one place, then scope codes to a full-price collection instead of the whole store. That holds only as long as every compare-at price is maintained and every new code, including the ones your apps generate, is pointed at the right collection at the moment it is created.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <h2 class="faq-q">Why is my discount code applying on top of already reduced prices?</h2>
      <p class="faq-a">Because to Shopify a markdown is a price and a code is a discount, and the rules that prevent stacking only operate between discounts. When you reduce a product's price and keep the old price as compare-at, the discount engine never registers a discount, so a sitewide code sees a normal price and applies in full. If both the sale and the code were built as actual discounts, the combination settings could keep them apart, but most stores run sales as price edits because that is what drives the storefront strikethrough, the sale badges, and the collection sorting. The result is a double discount that is real to your margin and invisible to the settings page that looks like it should prevent it.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <h2 class="faq-q">How do I stop welcome popup codes from working on sale items?</h2>
      <p class="faq-a">The hard part is that popup, loyalty, and review apps mint their own codes, usually sitewide, and a setting you fix today does not govern the codes the app issues tomorrow. Some apps offer collection restrictions, many do not, and each one is a separate setting to remember. The dependable approach is to enforce the rule at the store rather than inside each app: watch for new codes as they are created, scope them to your full-price collection the moment they appear, and guard checkout so a code that still meets a marked-down item resolves to the single best discount instead of stacking. That way the policy holds no matter which app minted the code or when it was issued.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

